00:31:48.263 --> 00:31:50.430
So congratulations, I mean,
what you've accomplished

00:31:50.430 --> 00:31:51.350
is really stellar.

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:53.480
DUNCAN SHEIK: Thank you.

00:31:53.480 --> 00:31:56.750
AUDIENCE: Two questions,
one, Jessie and Molly,

00:31:56.750 --> 00:32:00.413
did I catch the name similarity?

00:32:00.413 --> 00:32:02.330
MOLLY GORDON: We don't
have a name similarity,

00:32:02.330 --> 00:32:03.860
but that's my mom.

00:32:03.860 --> 00:32:07.820
AUDIENCE: Oh, yes, how is
it working with your mom?

00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:09.100
MOLLY GORDON: It's wonderful.

00:32:09.100 --> 00:32:10.760
AUDIENCE: And second
question, so I don't have to--

00:32:10.760 --> 00:32:11.210
MOLLY GORDON: No, please.

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:12.502
AUDIENCE: --ruin the flow here.

00:32:12.502 --> 00:32:14.570
Is there going to
be a cast recording?

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:16.550
DUNCAN SHEIK: We are
attempting to do it

00:32:16.550 --> 00:32:18.910
actually like in 10 days.

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:21.740
But, yeah, there's
still a couple things

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:22.670
we need to figure out.

00:32:22.670 --> 00:32:23.907
But definitely one.

00:32:23.907 --> 00:32:24.740
AUDIENCE: Good luck.

00:32:24.740 --> 00:32:25.620
It'll be compelling.

00:32:25.620 --> 00:32:26.813
DUNCAN SHEIK: Yeah, thanks.

00:32:26.813 --> 00:32:28.300
AUDIENCE: Wait you didn't
answer my question.

00:32:28.300 --> 00:32:29.883
MOLLY GORDON: Oh,
working with my mom.

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:34.220
I feel incredibly
lucky, because--

00:32:34.220 --> 00:32:38.010
so, I've known all of these
people since I was a kid.

00:32:38.010 --> 00:32:41.390
So it feels kind of
like this huge family.

00:32:41.390 --> 00:32:44.360
And then my mom and I
are incredibly close.

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:45.740
I'm an only child.

00:32:45.740 --> 00:32:49.670
And getting to work with her
has been the greatest gift.

00:32:49.670 --> 00:32:52.580
And she sets such
a professional tone

00:32:52.580 --> 00:32:54.710
with me and with the whole cast.

00:32:54.710 --> 00:32:56.180
But also, it's
wonderful, because I

00:32:56.180 --> 00:33:00.080
think she can shoot
me an eye movement,

00:33:00.080 --> 00:33:02.220
and I know a little
bit maybe more quickly

00:33:02.220 --> 00:33:04.100
what she's feeling.

00:33:04.100 --> 00:33:09.470
But I think we look up to
people, like Cassavetes,

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:10.680
that work with their family.

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:12.930
And this is our first real
time working together.

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.590
And it's been incredible.

00:33:15.590 --> 00:33:18.590
So I hope that I will get
that opportunity again.

00:33:18.590 --> 00:33:20.840
BERNIE TELSEY: I would just
say being a witness of it,

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:22.970
it's that thing that
you were talking

00:33:22.970 --> 00:33:26.150
about, what makes a wonderful
collaboration, the trust.

00:33:26.150 --> 00:33:29.210
And this, you know,
it's just the silences.

00:33:29.210 --> 00:33:31.310
And there's such a trust
that you're willing--

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:32.977
because so much about
working on theater

00:33:32.977 --> 00:33:35.030
is having to trust
the person that you're

00:33:35.030 --> 00:33:36.800
taking a direction from.

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:39.690
I mean, because you're
working on your own process.

00:33:39.690 --> 00:33:43.910
And once there's that trust,
you just are able to listen.

00:33:43.910 --> 00:33:47.420
And I was lucky enough to work
with another father-son team,

00:33:47.420 --> 00:33:51.960
Peter Hedges and Lucas Hedges,
on the movie, "Ben is Back."

00:33:51.960 --> 00:33:53.720
But it was the
same kind of thing

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:56.750
that you both had, that
it allows you to go

00:33:56.750 --> 00:33:59.420
that much further, I think.

00:33:59.420 --> 00:34:03.100
AUDIENCE: I also saw the
show and it was fantastic.

00:34:03.100 --> 00:34:05.600
I was wondering, if you've been
working on the show for nine

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:09.449
years, you talked about
bringing the choreographers on,

00:34:09.449 --> 00:34:11.510
at what stage does that happen.

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:12.942
And like the set design as well.

00:34:12.942 --> 00:34:14.900
I mean, I imagine that
can't have been going on

00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:15.817
for nine years, right?

00:34:15.817 --> 00:34:18.639
So what's the timeline of
all that coming together?

00:34:18.639 --> 00:34:21.110
DUNCAN SHEIK: It was
late in the process.

00:34:21.110 --> 00:34:24.114
I'm trying to remember when
the choreographers came on.

00:34:24.114 --> 00:34:25.989
JESSIE NELSON: These
came after [INAUDIBLE]..

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:26.960
BERNIE TELSEY: Yeah,
the choreography

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:28.745
came on before the
production at MCC

00:34:28.745 --> 00:34:32.110
in a little bit of a
choreographic lab beforehand.

00:34:32.110 --> 00:34:35.000
DUNCAN SHEIK: Yeah, and then
things like the orchestrations,

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:38.480
which you know, Simon Hale did
these really beautiful things

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:41.510
for just three instruments,
a brass, a reed and a cello.

00:34:41.510 --> 00:34:43.639
That happened quite at the end.

00:34:43.639 --> 00:34:45.710
Jason Hart did the
vocal arrangements.

00:34:45.710 --> 00:34:49.580
And he's been working on
it for maybe five years.

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:52.940
But a lot of these things
did come together quite late

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:54.159
in the process.

00:34:54.159 --> 00:34:55.909
STEVEN SATER: I think,
Duncan and I always

00:34:55.909 --> 00:34:58.730
joke that we do
workshops for a living.

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:00.620
And part of it is--

00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:02.090
MOLLY GORDON: They
pay really well.

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:03.632
STEVEN SATER: That's
what I'm saying.

00:35:03.632 --> 00:35:06.170
It's the state of theater
with new musicals,

00:35:06.170 --> 00:35:07.460
you're really on your own.

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:10.100
I mean, we began this
literally on our own.

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:14.360
But then you kind of go
from shelter to shelter.

00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:16.530
Aspen has you out
for two weeks and you

00:35:16.530 --> 00:35:18.530
get as much as you can
done, and you try and get

00:35:18.530 --> 00:35:19.738
some vocal arrangements done.

00:35:19.738 --> 00:35:21.720
You try and find
casts, like we found

00:35:21.720 --> 00:35:23.930
Noah Galvin to go to Aspen.

00:35:23.930 --> 00:35:27.250
But it's really all in
your head is the reality.

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:29.060
It was really Jessie
and I rewriting

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:33.020
stage directions of what we
imagined for those years.

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:36.935
And then there's a process
of choosing designers,

00:35:36.935 --> 00:35:40.250
of trying to find the right,
designers, which was months,

00:35:40.250 --> 00:35:40.910
you know.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:41.790
That was a long--

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:43.640
and then you're just
in it with them.

00:35:43.640 --> 00:35:45.110
You start designing.

00:35:45.110 --> 00:35:46.520
And you know--

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:48.770
I mean, I wasn't part of the
process working with them

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:49.760
like that.

00:35:49.760 --> 00:35:51.440
But it's very late in the game.

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:54.830
And suddenly, the
production-- and your casting.

00:35:54.830 --> 00:35:56.340
We had this rare fortune too.

00:35:56.340 --> 00:36:00.740
Let's just say that our producer
is also the leading casting

00:36:00.740 --> 00:36:02.290
director there is.

00:36:02.290 --> 00:36:03.500
And so we had--

00:36:03.500 --> 00:36:06.980
we had a lot of rehearsal,
a lot of auditions.

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:09.560
And I think what Bernie and
Jessie managed to do together

00:36:09.560 --> 00:36:11.780
was bring us a cast of stars.

00:36:11.780 --> 00:36:13.550
So you feel like
everyone in Wonderland

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:16.670
gets their star turn moment.

00:36:16.670 --> 00:36:18.110
You really do.

00:36:18.110 --> 00:36:19.152
BERNIE TELSEY: Thank you.

00:36:19.152 --> 00:36:21.610
AUDIENCE: Actually that was a
great lead in to my question.

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:22.940
So my question is for Bernie.

00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:24.440
Being the legendary
casting director

00:36:24.440 --> 00:36:27.805
that you are, but a
producer on this show,

00:36:27.805 --> 00:36:29.680
what was it like putting
the producer hat on?

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:32.610
And how are the differences
from a normal product

00:36:32.610 --> 00:36:34.720
that you work on in
the casting capacity?

00:36:34.720 --> 00:36:36.580
BERNIE TELSEY:
Yeah, I mean I love

00:36:36.580 --> 00:36:38.440
doing what we get to do at MCC.

00:36:38.440 --> 00:36:41.020
And there's a few of
us on the producing

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:42.310
staff and the artistic staff.

00:36:42.310 --> 00:36:44.710
But it was just
wonderful to get to be

00:36:44.710 --> 00:36:45.940
part of that collaboration.

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:47.770
A lot of times with
casting, you're

00:36:47.770 --> 00:36:49.690
done once the
auditions are done.

00:36:49.690 --> 00:36:52.600
And then you go and you see
the show at dress rehearsal

00:36:52.600 --> 00:36:54.270
or opening night.

00:36:54.270 --> 00:36:57.070
And for "Alice," to be part
of that process with the cast,

00:36:57.070 --> 00:36:59.527
and with Jessie,
and the authors,

00:36:59.527 --> 00:37:01.360
it's so different and
wonderful, because you

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:05.140
get to have your sort of
hand in the cake, you know,

00:37:05.140 --> 00:37:08.440
as you're making
it with everybody.

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:11.770
And seeing it change daily,
you know, from things

00:37:11.770 --> 00:37:14.620
that they were doing with
the story, or the staging,

00:37:14.620 --> 00:37:16.049
or the acting.

00:37:16.049 --> 00:37:16.882
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:19.710 --> 00:37:22.240
BERNIE TELSEY: Anybody else?

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:23.632
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:37:23.632 --> 00:37:25.340
I'm seeing the show
in a week and a half.

00:37:25.340 --> 00:37:28.540
So I'm even more so
excited than I was.

00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:30.010
Is there anything
you wish people

00:37:30.010 --> 00:37:33.947
knew coming into the show
that they might not already?

00:37:33.947 --> 00:37:35.530
BERNIE TELSEY: That's
a good question.

00:37:38.967 --> 00:37:41.050
JESSIE NELSON: I would say
it might be interesting

00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:44.980
for you to read the book,
just because it's always

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:48.100
interesting to examine the
source material of what's

00:37:48.100 --> 00:37:49.630
something sprung from.

00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:51.150
It's not necessary, as we said.

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:55.000
But it is interesting to
see how much of these themes

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.550
exist in the book.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:38:02.140
DUNCAN SHEIK: And I would
say, just know that, you know,

00:38:02.140 --> 00:38:04.240
I'm trying to put this
as politely as I can.

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:09.520
But I think Steven comes from a
tradition of Albee, and Pinter,

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:10.270
and Stoppard.

00:38:10.270 --> 00:38:11.980
And so there's a
lot of wordplay.

00:38:11.980 --> 00:38:14.590
And it's not always--

00:38:14.590 --> 00:38:17.660
it's something you really
have to sort of lean into

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:20.420
to get what's going
on to some extent.

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.790
And I think that's a good thing.

00:38:21.790 --> 00:38:25.130
Because it's important,
profound stuff.

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:30.340
But don't expect an evening's
light entertainment.

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:34.080
MOLLY GORDON: Yeah,
I would say also

00:38:34.080 --> 00:38:37.940
to really listen to the lyrics,
because they're so beautiful.

00:38:37.940 --> 00:38:42.400
And I think so many musicals
have such incredible lyrics.

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:43.900
But I think this
one specifically,

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:47.170
the word play is so genius.

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:50.470
And if you-- you have to
lean in a little bit more

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:53.150
to pick up on all of them.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:55.360
But if you can, lean,
I would lean in.

00:38:55.360 --> 00:38:57.318
DUNCAN SHEIK: If you can,
it's rewarding, yeah.

00:38:59.248 --> 00:39:01.040
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
you so much for coming.

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:03.310
I think this story of
"Alice in Wonderland"

00:39:03.310 --> 00:39:05.650
is really fantastical
and absurd.

00:39:05.650 --> 00:39:09.760
And it might relate like to
reality in different ways.

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:12.130
How did you choose
the setting, to be

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:14.950
in London and during
this particular time?

00:39:14.950 --> 00:39:18.580
And what other settings could
this story possibly relate to?

00:39:20.728 --> 00:39:23.145
JESSIE NELSON: It could have
related to a lot of settings.

00:39:25.710 --> 00:39:31.560
For me personally, my dad
was a pilot in World War II.

00:39:31.560 --> 00:39:33.360
He was stationed in
London during the blitz

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:34.770
when he was 19.

00:39:34.770 --> 00:39:36.830
And he spent a lot of
time in the tube stations

00:39:36.830 --> 00:39:37.830
while London was bombed.

00:39:37.830 --> 00:39:41.258
So I grew up on those
stories of huddled

00:39:41.258 --> 00:39:43.800
together, and the girl that he
got a crush on, named Bubbles,

00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:45.300
while London was being bombed.

00:39:45.300 --> 00:39:47.340
And these amazing
stories of being

00:39:47.340 --> 00:39:51.510
a young man with no real
awareness of the situation,

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:53.250
of the soberness of
the situation that he

00:39:53.250 --> 00:39:54.360
was dealing with.

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:56.790
And Steven had a real
connection to that time,

00:39:56.790 --> 00:39:57.870
more in a literary way.

00:39:57.870 --> 00:39:59.350
You might speak to that.

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:01.080
But we came to--

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:03.390
that was kind of
effortless, coming together

00:40:03.390 --> 00:40:05.700
on the notion of being
in a tube station.

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:07.200
It seemed like the
perfect metaphor,

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:09.980
because Alice falls
down the hole.

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:12.420
And so to begin our
story underground,

00:40:12.420 --> 00:40:14.850
where she's already fallen
down a really dark hole,

00:40:14.850 --> 00:40:17.700
seemed like an
interesting point.

00:40:17.700 --> 00:40:20.250
STEVEN SATER: And it
seemed, there was--

00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:22.393
just furthering
everything Jessie said.

00:40:22.393 --> 00:40:24.310
There was-- I don't know
if you remember this,

00:40:24.310 --> 00:40:28.020
we worked on the show
in London at one point.

00:40:28.020 --> 00:40:30.520
And there was a terrible--
not when we were there,

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:33.060
but prior to our going,
there was a terrible--

00:40:33.060 --> 00:40:35.040
there was a terrorist
attack in a tube station.

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:36.910
It's happened repeatedly
around the world.

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:39.930
But bombs went off.

00:40:39.930 --> 00:40:42.330
And there's this
sense of the fragility

00:40:42.330 --> 00:40:44.010
of the world, and
our world today,

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:47.850
and the urgency, the
kind of urgent situation

00:40:47.850 --> 00:40:49.530
we can be living in.

00:40:49.530 --> 00:40:51.360
I think also as the
piece developed,

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:53.460
because our cultural
landscape changed

00:40:53.460 --> 00:40:57.810
a lot over the last nine
years, I think we can say,

00:40:57.810 --> 00:41:00.750
we saw more and more people
living in encampments.

00:41:00.750 --> 00:41:03.970
We saw more and more
displaced individuals.

00:41:03.970 --> 00:41:10.320
So those themes, we began to
mine and look for within the--

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:13.583
how the material could serve the
story we were trying to tell.

00:41:13.583 --> 00:41:15.000
Now I think "Alice
in Wonderland,"

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.010
part of what's so amazing
about "Alice's Adventures

00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:19.302
in Wonderland" and all the
"Alice in Wonderland" movies

00:41:19.302 --> 00:41:23.350
is, it can be reinvented
in so many ways.

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:25.530
DUNCAN SHEIK: Yeah, I
mean for about 20 minutes,

00:41:25.530 --> 00:41:29.020
I really thought it should be
set in some dystopian future,

00:41:29.020 --> 00:41:31.980
like where the world has
completely fallen apart.

00:41:31.980 --> 00:41:37.470
But I was quickly disabused
of that notion by these guys.

00:41:37.470 --> 00:41:40.020
But I do think it's
a story that could

00:41:40.020 --> 00:41:43.860
be told in many
different contexts, yeah.

00:41:43.860 --> 00:41:44.820
